abuse </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of  licence payers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> money</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> awarding huge sums to surplus executives and managers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">any</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, like me, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have been shoc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ked by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">disgraceful</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> cover up of foul and criminal activities undertaken on BBC premises</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> over many years in the past.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> In the recent Savile case, the “whistle-blowing” had ITN to thank, not the BBC itself.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">used to wake up routinely to the Radio 4 Today </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programme, but gradually became disillusioned</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and irritated by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> it’s content</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  I </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">find that I can no longer listen </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">or watch BBC News </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:1